legacy.name: Brent D. Sadler

result.text:
Tone Deaf Navy Shipbuilding Plans

Recently CBO’s Eric Labs completed the annual mandated review of the costs and effectiveness of the Navy’s long-range shipbuilding plan. This report is excellent and shows why these plans continue to miss the mark.

First, the goal has been since 2016 to deliver a fleet of 355 warships by mid next decade - we are nowhere near this goal nor seriously progressing in that direction. Meanwhile, China is increasingly undeterred in taking on the US this decade.

Second, all options presented by the Navy decrease ship numbers as well as firepower this decade. Only by early next decade do any options proposed begin to increase critical naval capacity.

Third, costs seemingly increase on a per hull basis while delivering fewer ships. The insight here is that larger block purchases should be pursued and more stable funding mechanism developed to take advantage of economies of scale and provide more stability to shipyard… by the way this would see increased capital investment to grow workforces and shipbuilding capacities.

Four, no option meets the Congressionally mandated amphibious fleet level of 31 warships. Senator Sullivan has taken exceptional outrage on this point.

Five, AUKUS clearly will impact US nuclear attack submarine force size without more investment today in growing production rates in excess of 3.0 subs a year this decade.

Six, Congress has supported increased shipbuilding costs but Navy keeps undercutting actual costs which is eroding trust. Again, better procurement plans needed.

See the report here: https://t.co/R8R53dyDYY.
